## Port Scanning Types

### TCP Connect Scan (`-sT`)
```bash
nmap -sT 10.10.10.10
```

**How it works:**
- Completes full TCP 3-way handshake
- SYN → SYN-ACK → ACK
- Reliable but detectable

**Pros:**
- Works without root privileges
- Accurate results

**Cons:**
- Logged by target systems
- Slower than SYN scan
- Easier to detect

---

### SYN Scan (`-sS`) - Stealth Scan
```bash
sudo nmap -sS 10.10.10.10
```

**How it works:**
- Sends SYN packet
- Receives SYN-ACK if port open
- Sends RST (reset) instead of ACK
- Never completes handshake

**Pros:**
- Stealthier (doesn't complete connection)
- Faster than TCP connect
- Default scan type (if run as root)

**Cons:**
- Requires root/admin privileges
- Still detectable by modern IDS/IPS

---

### UDP Scan (`-sU`)
```bash
sudo nmap -sU 10.10.10.10
```

**How it works:**
- Sends UDP packets to ports
- No response = port might be open (UDP is stateless)
- ICMP Port Unreachable = port closed

**Important UDP services:**
- DNS (53)
- DHCP (67/68)
- SNMP (161)
- NTP (123)

**Pros:**
- Discovers UDP services (often forgotten)

**Cons:**
- Very slow (UDP has no handshake)
- Less reliable results

