## Scan Timing

Nmap has timing templates to control scan speed vs stealth.

### Timing Templates (`-T`)
```bash
nmap -T0 10.10.10.10  # Paranoid (extremely slow, max stealth)
nmap -T1 10.10.10.10  # Sneaky (very slow, stealth)
nmap -T2 10.10.10.10  # Polite (slower, less network load)
nmap -T3 10.10.10.10  # Normal (default)
nmap -T4 10.10.10.10  # Aggressive (faster, noisier)
nmap -T5 10.10.10.10  # Insane (fastest, very noisy)
```

### When to use each:

**T0-T2 (Stealth):**
- Penetration testing with IDS evasion
- Avoiding detection
- Time not a concern

**T3 (Normal):**
- Balanced scanning
- Default choice
- Reasonable speed and stealth

**T4 (Aggressive):**
- Fast network scans
- When detection doesn't matter
- Internal network audits

**T5 (Insane):**
- Very fast networks only
- High chance of missing results
- Rarely recommended

